Team ZNF777 Published ChIP-seq Pipeline Logbook

1-8-26

Note: The main difference with this run is that all fastq.gz files were ran through TrimGalore to maintain consistency.

Background

This logbook provides a summary of our ChIP-seq analysis pipeline. It includes both the actual commands used to generate the data, as well as clarifying comments throughout.

Data

Data generation: Illumina Indexing Kits (#R400695 and R400697) SMARTer DNA Single Index Kit was used for the construction of sequencing libraries. This data is reverse stranded data and was sequenced on an Illumina NovaSeq 6000 at the NICHD Molecular Genomics Core Facility.

The preliminary analysis was done on the NIH HPC computing cluster (biowulf). https://hpc.nih.gov/

I used the GRCh38.p13 human genome gtf and fasta files from GenCode (PRI), see details below for how to obtain those.

Links for used packages and websites with versions used:

  • FastQC (Quality check). I used version 0.11.9 https://www.bioinformatics.babraham.ac.uk/projects/fastqc/
  • Trim_galore (fastq.gz trimming). I used version 0.6.7. https://github.com/FelixKrueger/TrimGalore/blob/master/Docs/Trim_Galore_User_Guide.md#step-2-adapter-trimming
  • Samtools (index aligned .bam files): I used version 1.15 http://www.htslib.org/
  • bowtie2 (alignment). I used version 2.4.5 http://bowtie-bio.sourceforge.net/bowtie2/index.shtml
  • Deeptools bamCoverage (bw file generation). I used version 3.8.5-1 https://deeptools.readthedocs.io/en/develop/content/tools/bamCoverage.html#Read%20coverage%20normalization%20options
  • macs2 (for peakcalling) : https://pypi.org/project/MACS2/ or also https://manpages.ubuntu.com/manpages/xenial/man1/macs2_callpeak.1.html

A couple other useful tools:

  • GREAT (to see where your peaks are in relation to transcriptional start sites of genes): https://great.stanford.edu/great/public/html/
  • homer (to annotate peaks with nearby genes): I used version 4.11.1 http://homer.ucsd.edu/homer/ngs/annotation.html
  • bedtools (to intersect narrowPeak files to find overlap) https://bedtools.readthedocs.io/en/latest/
  • Conversion ENSEMBL identifiers to gene symbol: https://www.biotools.fr/mouse/ensembl_symbol_converter
  • Venn overlaps: https://bioinformatics.psb.ugent.be/webtools/Venn/
  • GO term analysis for gene lists: http://geneontology.org/#:~:text=The%20Gene%20Ontology%20(GO)%20knowledgebase,genetics%20experiments%20in%20biomedical%20research

Data download:

We used the Globus App to transfer files stored on the /scratch folder to our Biowulf data folders.

Mini warning

Always double-check you did what you wanted! The computer gives you what you ask for, not necessarily what you want.

Important Note

This logbook provides instructions for running our ChIP-seq analysis pipeline on a high performance computing cluster such as the Biowulf linux cluster. These commands may need to be modified to run on other machines.

Manage Files

Make a file that lists all the ChIP-seq fastq.gz file names without "R1_001.fastq.gz" and "R2_001.fastq.gz"

This can easily be done by listing all the files in the directory of interest ending in "R1_001.fastq.gz", excluding that substring, and saving it to a file which we will name files.

All steps were performed in an interactive session on the Biowulf HPC

In[]:
sinteractive --mem=24g --cpus-per-task=16

FastQC Analysis

To check the quality of the sequencing data we run a program called FastQC, which give you a graphical output to inspect the data quality in form of a .html file. Read the FastQC documentation see link above or copied here: https://www.bioinformatics.babraham.ac.uk/projects/fastqc/ to understand the output better. As FastQC is relatively quick to run I just use a basic bash script I write in nano and run it like this. The script specifies the location of input directory (dir). Caution/little exercise: It may be the output does not land in the folder we want it but in the input directory; we can fix the script if so (or just move the files manually).

First, create a FastQC.sh bash script.

In[]:
nano FastQC_paired.sh; nano FastQC_single.sh
In[]:
#!/bin/bash
#SBATCH --job-name=FastQCpaired
#SBATCH --ntasks=1
#SBATCH --cpus-per-task=32
#SBATCH --time=0-64:00:00
#SBATCH --output=outfile.%j
#SBATCH --error=errfile.%j
dir=/data/gallegosda/GEO/Published_ChIP-seq/fastq/paired
module load fastqc; cd $dir; mkdir FastQC; cd FastQC; fastqc ../*.fastq.gz

Submit the batch script.

In[]:
sbatch FastQC_paired.sh; sbatch FastQC_single.sh

FastQC reported that several of our files had high Adapter Content. These were trimmed using TrimGalore. For example:

This example can be interactively reviewed here: https://senftteam777.github.io/ChIPseq_logbook/preTrimGalore.html

TrimGalore; NOTE: today I tried TrimGalore on everything

See manual: https://github.com/FelixKrueger/TrimGalore/blob/master/Docs/Trim_Galore_User_Guide.md#step-2-adapter-trimming

USAGE: trim_galore [options] <filename(s)>

  • --paired
    • This option performs length trimming of quality/adapter/RRBS trimmed reads for paired-end files. To pass the validation test, both sequences of a sequence pair are required to have a certain minimum length which is governed by the option --length (see above). If only one read passes this length threshold the other read can be rescued (see option --retain_unpaired).
    • Using this option lets you discard too short read pairs without disturbing the sequence-by-sequence order of FastQ files which is required by many aligners. Trim Galore! expects paired-end files to be supplied in a pairwise fashion, e.g. file1_1.fq file1_2.fq SRR2_1.fq.gz SRR2_2.fq.gz ... .

Write trimgalore bash script.

In[]:
nano trimgalore_paired.sh
In[]:
#!/bin/bash
#SBATCH --job-name=PairedTrimgalore
#SBATCH --ntasks=1
#SBATCH --cpus-per-task=32
#SBATCH --time=0-64:00:00
#SBATCH --output=outfile.%j
#SBATCH --error=errfile.%j
dir=/data/gallegosda/GEO/Published_ChIP-seq/fastq/paired
module load trimgalore; module load fastqc; cd $dir; trim_galore --paired --fastqc $1.fastq.gz $2.fastq.gz

Get Genome Files

Make Index for Bowtie2

See http://bowtie-bio.sourceforge.net/bowtie2/manual.shtml#the-bowtie2-build-indexer

Since we have both human and mouse samples, a bowtie2 index must be executed for each genome.

Human hg38 Index

Write human index bash script.

In[]:
nano bowtie2_index_GRCh38.sh
In[]:
#!/bin/bash
#SBATCH --job-name=bowtie2_index
#SBATCH --ntasks=1
#SBATCH --cpus-per-task=16
#SBATCH --time=0-64:00:00
#SBATCH --output=outfile.%j
#SBATCH --error=errfile.%j

module load bowtie/2;
bowtie2-build \
-f /data/gallegosda/GEO/ChIP-seq/fastq/genome/hg38/GRCh38.primary_assembly.genome.fa GRCh38

##### Bowtie2 (single-end)
in_dir=/data/gallegosda/GEO/Published_ChIP-seq/fastq/single
Bowtie2_Index=/data/gallegosda/GEO/Published_ChIP-seq/fastq/genome/genome/hg38/bowtie2/GRCh38
bams=/data/gallegosda/GEO/Published_ChIP-seq/aligned

bowtie2 \
  --local \
  --very-sensitive-local \
  --no-unal \
  --no-mixed \
  --no-discordant \
  --phred33 \
  -I 10 -X 700 \
  -p $(( SLURM_CPUS_PER_TASK - 2 )) \
  -x $Bowtie2_Index \
  -U $in_dir/$1_trimmed.fq.gz \
| samtools view -u - \
| samtools sort -o $bams/$1.sorted.bam -@ $(( SLURM_CPUS_PER_TASK - 2 )) \
2> $bams/$1.log

samtools index $bams/$1.sorted.bam

Mouse mm10 alignment

Write mouse mm10 alignment script.

In[]:
nano bowtie2_mm10_paired.sh
In[]:
##### Bowtie2
in_dir=/data/gallegosda/GEO/Published_ChIP-seq/fastq/paired
Bowtie2_Index=/data/gallegosda/GEO/Published_ChIP-seq/fastq/genome/genome/mm10/bowtie2/GRCm38
bams=/data/gallegosda/GEO/Published_ChIP-seq/aligned

(bowtie2 --local --very-sensitive-local --no-unal --no-mixed --no-discordant --phred33 -I 10 -X 700 \
-p $(( SLURM_CPUS_PER_TASK - 2 )) -x $Bowtie2_Index -1 $in_dir/$1_R1_val_1.fq.gz  -2 $in_dir/$1_R2_val_2.fq.gz | samtools view -u - | samtools sort - > $bams/$1.bam) 2>$bams/$1.log

samtools sort $bams/$1.bam -o $bams/$1.sorted.bam -@ $(( SLURM_CPUS_PER_TASK - 2 )) &&

samtools index $bams/$1.sorted.bam $bams/$1.sorted.bai &&

rm $bams/$1.bam

In[]:
##### deeptools_bamCoverage_hg38.sh
##### get genomesize from deeptools manual at https://deeptools.readthedocs.io/en/develop/content/feature/effectiveGenomeSize.html
in_dir=/data/gallegosda/GEO/Published_ChIP-seq/aligned
out_dir=/data/gallegosda/GEO/Published_ChIP-seq/fastq/bw

cd $in_dir; bamCoverage --bam $1.sorted.bam -o $out_dir/$1_SeqDepthNorm.bw \
    --binSize 10 \
    --normalizeUsing RPGC \
    --effectiveGenomeSize 2913022398 \
    --ignoreForNormalization chrX chrM \
    --extendReads 200 \
    -p $SLURM_CPUS_PER_TASK

Important Note

Since macs2 accepts samples and their appropriate inputs, these must be broken up per experiment.

Human hg38 macs2

hESC_H1_777

Make macs2 script for human.

In[]:
nano macs2_hg38.sh
In[]:
##### macs2_hg38.sh
in_dir=/data/gallegosda/GEO/ChIP-seq/fastq/align_these/aligned
out_dir=/data/gallegosda/GEO/ChIP-seq/fastq/align_these/aligned/macs2/hg38_macs2
cd $in_dir; macs2 callpeak -t $1.sorted.bam -c $2.sorted.bam -f BAMPE -g 2913022398 --outdir $out_dir -n $3

Make human macs2 swarm file. By convention, the sample name is placed first, followed by the input name. This is optionally followed by a descriptive name of the sample over input.

nano generate_matrix_2samples_hg38.sh
In[]:
in_dir_bw=/data/gallegosda/GEO/ChIP-seq/fastq/align_these/aligned/bw/hg38_bw
in_dir_bed=/data/gallegosda/GEO/ChIP-seq/fastq/align_these/aligned/macs2/hg38_macs2
out_dir=/data/gallegosda/GEO/ChIP-seq/fastq/align_these/aligned/matrix/hg38_matrix

computeMatrix reference-point --referencePoint center -R $in_dir_bed/$1_peaks.narrowPeak \
        --skipZeros \
        --sortRegions descend \
        -S $in_dir_bw/$2_ratioinput.bw \
        -b 1000 -a 1000 \
        -o $out_dir/$1_$2_ratio.mat.gz \
        --missingDataAsZero \
        -p $(( SLURM_CPUS_PER_TASK - 2 ));
plotHeatmap \
        -m $out_dir/$1_$2_ratio.mat.gz \
        -out $out_dir/$1_$2_ratio.mat.png \
        --yMin 0 --yMax 15 \
        --labelRotation -90 \
        --regionsLabel $1 \
        --colorList darkblue,lightgoldenrodyellow,darkred

in_dir_bw=/data/gallegosda/GEO/ChIP-seq/fastq/align_these/aligned/bw/mm10_bw
in_dir_bed=/data/gallegosda/GEO/ChIP-seq/fastq/align_these/aligned/macs2/mm10_macs2
out_dir=/data/gallegosda/GEO/ChIP-seq/fastq/align_these/aligned/matrix/mm10_matrix

computeMatrix reference-point --referencePoint center -R $in_dir_bed/$1_peaks.narrowPeak \
        --skipZeros \
        --sortRegions descend \
        -S $in_dir_bw/$2_ratioinput.bw \
        -b 1000 -a 1000 \
        -o $out_dir/$1_$2_ratio.mat.gz \
        --missingDataAsZero \
        -p $(( SLURM_CPUS_PER_TASK - 2 ));
plotHeatmap \
        -m $out_dir/$1_$2_ratio.mat.gz \
        -out $out_dir/$1_$2_ratio.mat.png \
        --yMin 0 --yMax 15 \
        --labelRotation -90 \
        --regionsLabel $1 \
        --colorList darkblue,lightgoldenrodyellow,darkred
